  tierAlgorithm: { description: "Multiple triggers + high income + significant deductions -> tier2. Single trigger or low income -> tier1.", tier2Conditions: ["primaryTriggers === 'capital_gains_options' || primaryTriggers === 'tax_shelter'", "capitalGains === 'over_500k' || capitalGains === '200k_to_500k'", "stockOptions === 'over_200k' || stockOptions === '50k_to_200k'", "charitableDonations === 'over_50k'", "otherDeductions === 'significant'", "totalIncome === 'over_500k'"], tier2Flags: [] },
  calculatorRuleBox: { label: "The rule — Canadian AMT (ITA s127.5-127.55, revised 2024)", body: "AMT is a parallel tax calculation. You pay the HIGHER of regular federal tax or AMT. AMTI additions (vs regular income): capital gains at 100% (vs 50%/2/3), stock option benefit 100% (50% deduction reversed), 50% of non-capital losses from shelters, 50% of resource deductions. Deductions limited: employment expenses 50%, carrying charges 50%, certain losses. Non-refundable credits at 50% of regular (charitable donation, tuition, medical — some exceptions). Formula: AMT = (AMTI − $173,205 exemption) × 20.5% − permitted credits. AMT credit carryforward (excess of AMT over regular tax) applies in future years when regular tax exceeds AMT — indefinite period. Quebec has its own separate provincial AMT." },
