  crosslink: { title: "Selling an appreciated asset? Check flipping rule first", body: "The AMT triggers on large capital gains. If the asset is a residential property held under 365 days, the flipping rule deems profit as business income — which interacts with AMT differently. Use the Property Flipping Tax Trap auditor alongside this AMT analysis.", url: "/can/check/property-flipping-tax-trap", label: "Property Flipping Tax Trap →" },
  lawBarSummary: "Canada AMT Shock Auditor — Income Tax Act (Canada) Part I Division E.1 s127.5-127.55. 2024 reforms: AMT rate 20.5% (was 15%); exemption $173,205 (was $40,000; indexed). AMT base: AMTI = regular income + 100% capital gains (vs 50%/66.67%) + reversed 50% stock option deduction + 50% of certain losses + donation credit at 50% of regular. Formula: (AMTI − $173,205) × 20.5% − permitted credits. Pay greater of regular tax or AMT. Excess = AMT credit carryforward recoverable indefinitely in future years when regular tax exceeds AMT. Common triggers: large capital gains + heavy deductions; stock option exercises with 50% deduction claimed; donations of appreciated securities. Quebec has separate provincial AMT. Form T691 filed with T1.",
  lawBarBadges: ["CRA", "Income Tax Act s127.5", "20.5% AMT Rate from 2024", "$173,205 Exemption 2024", "100% Capital Gains in AMTI", "AMT Credit Carryforward Available"],
